column11: Italy is legally required to hold a general election in 2018. The populist Five Star Movement finished third in the 2013 general election and has seen strong support in recent polling (Reuters, CNBC, Quarts, Stratfor). The Five Star Movement has so far refused alliances with other parties, but the new electoral law incentivizes broad pre-election coalitions (Politico). Confused? Check our FAQ or ask us for help.

The obvious thing to note is that a new electoral system was brought in just a couple of months ago, making comparison with previous elections fairly difficult. The new law is summarised here: https://globalriskinsights.com/2017/11/italy-rosatellum-bis-primer/ The key features are: - There will be 630 Deputies elected to the Chamber - A PR/FPTP split, with 37% of the Deputies elected on FPTP (232) and 61% on PR (386). (12 Deputies are also elected to represent overseas populations) - The country is split into 20 constituencies with a varying number of Deputies elected

In the December opinion polls, M5S polls about 28% on average (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Opinion_polling_for_the_Italian_general_election%2C_2018#2018_2). This should be enough for about 120 out of the 398 proportional seats. Can they get 80+ out of the 230 first-past-the post seats? The first-past-the-post system rewards large parties with widespread popularity, which is good for M5S. However, if the center-right coalition wants to have any chance to govern, they should agree in advance to coordinate in the run for the first-past-the post seats. This would sharply reduce the M5S advantage.

Movimento Cinque Stelle is remaining true to its political identity as a "pure" opposition movement by not forming a pre election coalition. M5S's anti establishment populist identity and message appeals successfully to eurosceptics, and a youthful, disenfranchised population. However the political culture and nature of politics in Italy ultimately necessitates and encourages coalition formation. It seems that M5S has painted itself into a corner with its message eventhough Luigi Di Maio is putting forth a slicker and slightly more moderate image. The only problem is this message may start overlapping with the right-wing Forza, League and a potential centrist PD coalition who have more regional ties and historically a more persistent culturally ingrained message. Berlusconi, a master at coalition formation, will absorb centrists falling away from the PD coalition. M5S is doing well in the national polling however, the new election law allows only one pick on each ballot. It is quite possible that people with regional interests will forgo the M5S candidate and stay with their regional alliances. M5S will not live up to expectations in the first-past-the-post ballot. If M5S starts polling a few points over 32% I will have to think about revising upward but I think that any coalition Berlusconi creates will prevail in the elections and capture the largest segment of the population which is between the ages of 40 and 54. "Old age and treachery will always beat youth and exuberance."
If anything, M5S seems to be gaining in the December polls (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Opinion_polling_for_the_Italian_general_election%2C_2018)

On recent polling, M5S score around 25-30%, giving 100-119 of the proportionally allocated seats in the chamber of deputies. Using the cube rule, the FPTP seats should be 63 for their current polling of 28%. Given that a simulation online gives 46 FPTP seats, they are clearly unfavourably distributed. But taking a simple multiplier as a first approximation of this bad distribution, this gives 31-88 FPTP seats in this same range, giving a total of 131-207 seats. So it is clear high probability should go the 88-200 range, but allowance should be made for late polling shifts and the uncertainty inherent in a new system with majoritarian aspects.
Five Star Movement will rise, like all populist movements across Europe, but not to more than 200 deputies.

M5S might come out stronger than expected: This dynamic will triggered by the slow, but steady decline of PD in the polls which leads many voters to strategically opt for M5S instead of the left coalition, out of fear that the Berlusconi/Salvini-team might otherwise win in a landslide.

The entry thresholds and the partial FPTP system explicitly encourage parties to enter into coalition agreements before the elections. Parties risk being marginalised when they fail in the FPRP districts and win only a fraction of the PR seats, or, even worse, fail to cross the thresholds. Moreover, the 10% hurdle that is set for coalitions suggests that smaller parties have little option but to join either the centre-left bloc (CSX) or the centre-right bloc (CDX).

I think that to receive less than 88 seats, they would have to do much worse than current polling indicates or they would have to be crushed by an alliance of other parties that gained 40 % of the vote, which alliance currently does not exist. Besides, Forza Italia and Lega Nord together wouldn't very likely reach 40 %.

There is an indication that Silvio Berlusconi might be making a come back into politics as the head of the right wing coalition. While it is no certainty the right wing coalition seems to be one of the more likely ones that could both form a coalition ahead of election and thus receive the 40% of vote to achieve majority in the parliament. https://www.csmonitor.com/World/Europe/2017/1206/Berlusconi-s-improbable-return-to-politics-Why-Italy-is-giving-him-another-look The centre-right coalition had strong results in the Sicily regional vote managing an almost 40% of the total vote. M5S came second achieving 34,5% of the votes. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sicilian_regional_election,_2017 Looking back at the last parliamentary elections it clearly shows that Sicily is one of the regions in Italy that is divided amongst center-right coalition voters and M5S voters. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Italian_general_election,_2013#/media/File:Italian_2013_elections.png

The 2018 Italian general election is due to be held no later than 20 May 2018, that is to say no later than the last Sunday of the seventy days after the natural expiration of the current five-year parliamentary term on 15 March 2018. Voters will elect the 630 members of the Chamber of Deputies and the 315 elective members of the Senate of the Republic for the 18th term of the Italian Parliament.

Populist parties have faced a hard time recently with elections, not being able to rally enough support to push them into power. A couple of exceptions include AfD in Germany which recently won their first ever seats in Parliament and the ruling parties in Hungary and Poland. While I could predict the Five Star Movement increasing their share of seats slightly given how messy politics is in Italy right now, I have a hard time seeing any way for them to double their seats to more than 200.

I think M5S does better than its current position (87 seats) and they have improved significantly over the last four years. That being said I don't think they actually do as well their polls currently say (they're leading) because they seem like a protest vote and its much easier to protest between elections than at an election.
